<br>
As far as Germany NOT being a fascist nation...I never claimed such. In fact, I hold it as THE fascist nation of modern times. My debate is over the right-wing label. True, Hitler won on a platform of Anti-Communism. But, it was not a platform based on rejecting a socialist agenda. Rather, rejecting the ideals of mid-century Communism, which greatly differed from those espoused by traditional Socialist ideals. However, all you need to do is compare the governments of Stalin and Hitler side by side and you will see many more similarities than differences. Hitler replaced the weak leftist government and instituted one of his own which was more centralized and Socialist than the former. Whether or not you would call it right-wing or left wing is dependent upon your understanding of the political spectrum. My contention is that it does not make any sense for a government to be &quot;extremely right-wing&quot; when &quot;extremely right-wing&quot; flies in the face of the concept of a maintainable totalitarian regime. <br>
<br>
Maybe we are going about this in the wrong way. The fact is Fascism is Fascism. Whatever way you look at it, when a government takes a hard line toward centralization of power and limitation of rights it is a fascist regime. I personally believe that the slow and subtle shift toward a leftist society will give rise to such a regime with greater success than otherwise. It is my opinion that the more government social programs you institute, the more you spend on welfare and assistance programs, the more repsonsibility you shift from individuals to the government, the greater the chance that a dependent population will emerge, thus making it a simple matter to establish and maintain a totalitarian regime. <br>
<br>
It might be prudent to set such a regime apart from either &quot;side.&quot; There are many possibilities for the establishment of such a regime. One could be the abolishment of moral center such as was seen in the USSR and Germany. On the other hand, extreme Fundamentalism could give rise to an authoritarian rule, similar in result, but different in purpose. I would contend that the Fundamentalists are not right-wingers due to the necessity for a strong central figure or group. On the other side, it is apparent to me that the breakdown of a moral center is consistant with Marxist ideals, thus following closely to the left. Therefore, we are left with a conundrum. These examples do not truly follow the path to the left or right in a straight line. Possibly, they branch off at some point. I am not sure. It is obvious that though, I might have presented it as a black and white issue, while it might not be such.<br>
<br>
Nonetheless, I despise the ideals which take responsibility away from the individual and shift it to the artificial entity,  which breeds and cultivates interdependence and submission.<br>
<br>
LOL. And to the person who said they would not want to live under a Socialist government, in Sweden they pay about 85% to the income tax. That is in a quasi-Socialist government. I am not sure I would like that either.<br>
<br>
In seriousness, my apologies for dogmaticism and venomous speech. Maybe I will stay away from the political threads and let the leftists have their threads. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
